16
00:00:57,556 --> 00:00:59,423
Before diving into localization

17
00:00:59,448 --> 00:01:03,244
it’s helpful to first situate 
this concept among related concepts

18
00:01:03,470 --> 00:01:07,595
that deal with producing multilingual
products for international audiences.

19
00:01:08,483 --> 00:01:12,366
Globalization deals with the infrastructure
that enterprises put in place

20
00:01:12,391 --> 00:01:14,795
to carry out international operations.

21
00:01:15,530 --> 00:01:19,740
Internationalization is the development 
of software that is culturally neutral

22
00:01:20,155 --> 00:01:22,280
with the localization-ready architecture

23
00:01:22,305 --> 00:01:26,445
that can be customized 
to locales during localization.

24
00:01:27,422 --> 00:01:31,165
Localization is the adaptation 
of products and services

25
00:01:31,190 --> 00:01:33,460
to specific locales in the world.

26
00:01:34,182 --> 00:01:37,467
Translation is the work that’s done 
to render the language

27
00:01:37,492 --> 00:01:40,015
of an organization’s communications

28
00:01:40,303 --> 00:01:45,146
products and services to the language
variant spoken in a specific locale.

29
00:01:46,960 --> 00:01:50,348
In translation, words like 
“equivalent” and “accurate”

30
00:01:50,388 --> 00:01:54,216
are often used to describe the writing 
that results from translation.

31
00:01:54,809 --> 00:01:58,879
However, it’s important to note that 
by virtue of being in a different language

32
00:01:59,258 --> 00:02:02,953
aspects of the meaning of the 
source content will be lost

33
00:02:03,293 --> 00:02:05,547
and the target language 
will also add meaning

34
00:02:05,572 --> 00:02:08,047
that was not present 
in the so-called original.

35
00:02:09,986 --> 00:02:14,111
The components of the GILT framework
are interrelated and interdependent

36
00:02:14,491 --> 00:02:18,030
since the localization of products 
implies the need to navigate law

37
00:02:18,421 --> 00:02:22,741
hire local talent and support users 
at all stages of their customer journey.

38
00:02:25,182 --> 00:02:27,276
When working toward global market expansion

39
00:02:27,750 --> 00:02:32,008
globalization and internationalization 
form part of the main highway.

40
00:02:32,625 --> 00:02:34,382
However, some organizations

41
00:02:34,867 --> 00:02:36,711
eager to reach new markets quickly

42
00:02:37,187 --> 00:02:40,031
opt to bypass directly to localization

43
00:02:40,544 --> 00:02:44,615
and then have to deal with inefficient 
processes that require constant rework

44
00:02:45,096 --> 00:02:47,643
inconsistent brand messaging across markets

45
00:02:48,036 --> 00:02:51,239
technical challenges in adapting 
products for different locales

46
00:02:51,608 --> 00:02:54,944
and higher long-term costs 
due to the need for retrofitting.

47
00:02:55,977 --> 00:03:00,407
While localization strategy shapes 
an effective globalization strategy

48
00:03:00,903 --> 00:03:03,965
it is often relegated 
to a downstream process

49
00:03:04,008 --> 00:03:05,937
in the product development lifecycle.

50
00:03:06,783 --> 00:03:09,815
Localization teams are often 
handed minimum viable

51
00:03:09,840 --> 00:03:11,492
or fully featured products

52
00:03:11,812 --> 00:03:13,969
that have been validated 
for their original market

53
00:03:13,994 --> 00:03:16,313
but that are not prepared for localization.

54
00:03:19,200 --> 00:03:22,028
Let’s take software internationalization 
as an example.

55
00:03:22,923 --> 00:03:27,853
Key aspects of internationalization to 
ready software for localization includes:

56
00:03:28,212 --> 00:03:32,610
Externalizing strings by moving 
all user-facing text out of the code

57
00:03:32,984 --> 00:03:34,922
and into separate resource files

58
00:03:35,310 --> 00:03:39,192
and using string IDs in the code
instead of hardcoded text.

59
00:03:39,994 --> 00:03:43,376
Ensuring that the application 
uses Unicode encoding

60
00:03:43,458 --> 00:03:45,059
such as UTF-8

61
00:03:45,440 --> 00:03:48,197
to support multiple languages
and character sets.

62
00:03:48,880 --> 00:03:50,748
Avoiding string concatenation

63
00:03:50,773 --> 00:03:54,616
by using parameterized strings 
instead of concatenating fragments

64
00:03:55,044 --> 00:03:57,810
as word order can
change in different languages.

65
00:03:58,473 --> 00:04:01,816
Allowing for text expansion 
in user interface design

66
00:04:02,218 --> 00:04:05,320
as some languages may 
require more space than others.

67
00:04:05,997 --> 00:04:08,271
For dates, times, and numbers

68
00:04:08,787 --> 00:04:12,810
using locale-aware data types that can
adjust to different formats.

69
00:04:13,589 --> 00:04:16,018
Avoiding the hardcoding of 
cultural assumptions

70
00:04:16,043 --> 00:04:18,610
by not assuming specific date formats

71
00:04:18,894 --> 00:04:21,254
currency symbols, or sorting orders.

72
00:04:22,276 --> 00:04:24,089
Supporting bidirectional text

73
00:04:24,114 --> 00:04:27,270
by ensuring that the UI 
can handle both left-to-right

74
00:04:27,550 --> 00:04:30,065
and right-to-left text directions.

75
00:04:30,717 --> 00:04:33,584
For operations like sorting 
or case conversion

76
00:04:34,044 --> 00:04:37,943
using locale-aware functions 
instead of language-specific ones.

77
00:04:38,697 --> 00:04:40,471
Implementing plural rules...

78
00:04:40,943 --> 00:04:43,208
Languages have varying plural forms

79
00:04:43,233 --> 00:04:46,724
and a plural rule system must 
be used to handle this correctly.

80
00:04:47,425 --> 00:04:49,831
Avoiding hardcoding images with text...

81
00:04:50,128 --> 00:04:54,323
Text should be kept separate
from images to allow for easy translation.

82
00:04:56,731 --> 00:04:58,878
Can you spot the
internationalization issues

83
00:04:58,902 --> 00:05:02,106
in this code generated
by Claude 3.5 Sonnet?

84
00:05:02,743 --> 00:05:06,962
There are concatenation issues in the plus
operations used to combine strings.

85
00:05:07,818 --> 00:05:12,646
There is a hardcoded date format of month-
day-year which is not universally used.

86
00:05:13,309 --> 00:05:17,137
The dollar symbol is hardcoded, 
which isn’t appropriate for all locales.

87
00:05:18,003 --> 00:05:22,128
There is a plural form handling issue 
in the conditional statement at the end.

88
00:05:22,680 --> 00:05:24,265
This simple if-else statement

89
00:05:24,289 --> 00:05:28,110
doesn’t account for languages 
with more complex plural rules.

90
00:05:28,958 --> 00:05:33,161
Finally, hardcoded string issues 
appear throughout the entire function.

91
00:05:33,721 --> 00:05:37,698
All user-facing strings should be 
externalized for translation.

92
00:05:39,556 --> 00:05:41,361
As these types of issues pile up

93
00:05:41,778 --> 00:05:44,544
that results in a higher
internationalization debt

94
00:05:45,132 --> 00:05:48,093
or the accumulation of
internationalization issues

95
00:05:48,118 --> 00:05:52,463
that need to be addressed before
effective localization can occur.

96
00:05:54,919 --> 00:05:56,716
Here’s an improved version of the code

97
00:05:56,741 --> 00:06:00,043
that addresses the
localization issues in the following ways.

98
00:06:00,677 --> 00:06:03,770
String concatenation was 
replaced with the dot format

99
00:06:03,795 --> 00:06:06,930
and get text methodologies 
for easier translation.

100
00:06:07,705 --> 00:06:11,447
Where we previously had a hardcoded 
date format and currency symbol

101
00:06:11,883 --> 00:06:16,148
we’re now using Babel's format date 
and format currency functions

102
00:06:16,425 --> 00:06:17,807
which are locale-aware.

103
00:06:18,410 --> 00:06:21,832
We’ve implemented a more 
comprehensive plural form handling

104
00:06:21,857 --> 00:06:26,428
that can be more easily translated 
to languages with complex plural rules.

105
00:06:27,272 --> 00:06:29,905
The user-facing strings 
are no longer hardcoded

106
00:06:29,930 --> 00:06:32,920
and are instead wrapped 
with the get text function

107
00:06:33,251 --> 00:06:34,712
making them translatable.

108
00:06:35,517 --> 00:06:38,369
Also, the locale parameter 
has now been added.

109
00:06:39,175 --> 00:06:41,715
The function now accepts a locale string

110
00:06:42,168 --> 00:06:45,496
allowing for easy switching
between different locales.

111
00:06:46,027 --> 00:06:49,449
Please note that to use this code, 
we’d need to install Babel.

112
00:06:50,180 --> 00:06:51,547
For a full implementation

113
00:06:51,572 --> 00:06:55,375
we’d also need to set up proper
translation files for get text

114
00:06:55,745 --> 00:06:59,425
but this code structure allows for
easy integration of translations.

115
00:07:01,296 --> 00:07:05,632
If you’ll allow me one more example 
of an internationalization issue,

116
00:07:06,089 --> 00:07:10,917
code also needs to be updated to handle 
name ordering in different languages.

117
00:07:11,448 --> 00:07:12,885
For example, in English

118
00:07:13,232 --> 00:07:14,857
the given name comes first

119
00:07:14,904 --> 00:07:17,747
and in Chinese
the family name comes first.

120
00:07:18,439 --> 00:07:20,478
Here’s an example of the output of code

121
00:07:20,503 --> 00:07:23,561
that has been adapted to
different name ordering conventions

122
00:07:24,050 --> 00:07:26,964
that also shows how the 
greeting itself can be translated.

123
00:07:29,429 --> 00:07:32,828
These are all issues that an 
AI coding assistant could be set up

124
00:07:32,853 --> 00:07:35,944
to help localization aware 
programmers to identify

125
00:07:36,311 --> 00:07:39,304
to ensure that
software is properly localized.

126
00:07:42,163 --> 00:07:43,170
Let’s move on.

127
00:07:43,269 --> 00:07:45,640
Let’s assume that proper globalization and

128
00:07:45,665 --> 00:07:48,566
internationalization frameworks are in place

129
00:07:49,047 --> 00:07:50,976
Now, let’s consider localization.

130
00:07:51,416 --> 00:07:54,010
This is a localization workflow model

131
00:07:54,035 --> 00:07:56,127
that I’ve taught for about seven years now.

132
00:07:56,680 --> 00:07:59,751
It’s based upon an illustration 
that I recently had published

133
00:07:59,776 --> 00:08:02,871
in the Handbook of the Language Industry 
in my chapter called

134
00:08:03,294 --> 00:08:07,021
“Translation and Localization 
Project and Process Managers.”

135
00:08:09,374 --> 00:08:10,835
Let’s walk through the workflow.

136
00:08:11,314 --> 00:08:14,298
In this workflow, 
a client submits a work request.

137
00:08:14,850 --> 00:08:17,850
Specifications, 
or the requirements for work

138
00:08:18,243 --> 00:08:20,282
are defined and then the work is quoted.

139
00:08:20,992 --> 00:08:23,257
Assuming that the client approves the quote

140
00:08:23,581 --> 00:08:25,081
preproduction begins.

141
00:08:25,575 --> 00:08:27,403
Resources are put into place.

142
00:08:27,733 --> 00:08:29,473
the project is prepared for production

143
00:08:29,497 --> 00:08:32,835
through such steps as
pre-editing the source text

144
00:08:33,329 --> 00:08:34,603
gathering terminology

145
00:08:35,107 --> 00:08:36,865
carrying out pseudo-translation

146
00:08:36,890 --> 00:08:40,702
to determine where text
expansion or contraction may take place

147
00:08:40,727 --> 00:08:44,875
in order to identify where adjustments 
to the overall design may be needed.

148
00:08:45,586 --> 00:08:47,242
The work is passed through

149
00:08:47,583 --> 00:08:51,184
machine and human translation in a
translation environment tool

150
00:08:51,609 --> 00:08:55,021
that separates the language for
translation from its packaging

151
00:08:55,046 --> 00:08:59,256
whether that packaging be a Word document 
or a website or some other structure.

152
00:08:59,709 --> 00:09:01,342
When the language work is complete

153
00:09:01,367 --> 00:09:05,582
the language is reincorporated
back into the design of the product.

154
00:09:05,959 --> 00:09:08,975
In-context and functionality 
checks take place

155
00:09:09,342 --> 00:09:11,818
and then finally the
work is delivered to the client.

156
00:09:13,723 --> 00:09:18,270
Now, a guiding principle in my work in 
translation and localization has been

157
00:09:18,862 --> 00:09:21,542
Time investments during 
front end stages yield

158
00:09:21,567 --> 00:09:24,914
yield the greatest efficiencies 
on back end processes.

159
00:09:25,547 --> 00:09:29,688
I’ve come to this principle after 
discovering unknowns during localization.

160
00:09:31,158 --> 00:09:33,814
For example, Khmer, a language of Cambodia

161
00:09:33,839 --> 00:09:37,470
uses different keyboard configurations 
to produce different fonts.

162
00:09:38,016 --> 00:09:41,282
If I need the content to be 
localized into a Unicode font

163
00:09:41,667 --> 00:09:45,120
I need to define that requirement 
upfront in specifications

164
00:09:45,145 --> 00:09:48,111
to avoid a great deal of 
rework further downstream.

165
00:09:50,404 --> 00:09:54,959
So, let’s start at the beginning and 
take a deeper look at specifications.

166
00:09:55,716 --> 00:09:59,856
For clarity, we’ll start with a 
working definition of specifications.

167
00:10:00,568 --> 00:10:04,615
According to ASTM International,
an international standards body

168
00:10:05,075 --> 00:10:06,645
specifications are the

169
00:10:06,670 --> 00:10:10,474
“explicit set of requirements 
to be satisfied by a material

170
00:10:10,868 --> 00:10:13,297
product, system, or service.”

171
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:17,442
Now, specifications are 
important in every industry.

172
00:10:18,053 --> 00:10:22,241
Specifications are particularly 
important in translation and localization

173
00:10:22,648 --> 00:10:25,320
because quality here is so subjective.

174
00:10:25,778 --> 00:10:29,254
If you ask a group of five translators
to translate the same content

175
00:10:29,279 --> 00:10:31,416
no two will produce the same translation

176
00:10:31,869 --> 00:10:35,361
and they’ll also have different ideas 
about the quality of each translation

177
00:10:35,783 --> 00:10:38,806
With specifications, 
the primary objective is therefore

178
00:10:38,831 --> 00:10:43,095
to take this fuzzy idea of 
translation and localization quality

179
00:10:43,533 --> 00:10:44,721
and make it objective.

180
00:10:45,158 --> 00:10:47,799
At the end of translation and localization

181
00:10:48,215 --> 00:10:50,824
if we’ve met the requirements 
in the specifications

182
00:10:51,134 --> 00:10:52,353
we have achieved quality

183
00:10:52,661 --> 00:10:55,544
so long as the specifications 
are accurate and complete.

184
00:10:56,107 --> 00:10:59,482
Defining accurate and complete 
specifications is no small matter.

185
00:10:59,979 --> 00:11:02,400
Specifications need 
to address the requirements

186
00:11:02,425 --> 00:11:05,774
of the requesters of the 
translation and localization services

187
00:11:06,102 --> 00:11:07,266
their end users

188
00:11:07,632 --> 00:11:09,695
and the teams producing the content.

189
00:11:10,299 --> 00:11:14,299
Specifications also need 
to make any implicit expectations

190
00:11:14,324 --> 00:11:19,637
of the receiving culture that may not be 
obvious to localization producers explicit.

191
00:11:21,590 --> 00:11:24,950
That’s why using standards-based 
specifications is so important

192
00:11:24,975 --> 00:11:28,412
in achieving desired outcomes 
in translation and localization.

193
00:11:30,318 --> 00:11:33,631
Let's discuss the standards-based 
specification template

194
00:11:33,656 --> 00:11:38,295
for translation and localization work that 
I've developed over the past seven years.

195
00:11:39,107 --> 00:11:42,458
This template is structured 
into various parameter groups.

196
00:11:43,170 --> 00:11:47,982
Project specifics outline the requirements 
for each project in a product line

197
00:11:48,409 --> 00:11:51,893
while the remaining parameter groups 
are meant to provide general guidelines

198
00:11:51,918 --> 00:11:54,221
applicable across the entire product line.

199
00:11:55,126 --> 00:11:59,158
Within these specifications, 
language work - often translation

200
00:11:59,539 --> 00:12:04,406
is defined in harmony 
with the definition used by FIT

201
00:12:04,832 --> 00:12:08,871
as work performed on the textual aspects 
of the content for rendering.

202
00:12:09,739 --> 00:12:12,200
Within these specifications, design work

203
00:12:12,410 --> 00:12:15,144
i.e. localization, is defined as

204
00:12:15,169 --> 00:12:18,827
work with non-textual aspects 
of the content for rendering.

205
00:12:19,656 --> 00:12:21,594
 According to the MQM framework

206
00:12:21,969 --> 00:12:26,930
“Design includes text, paragraph, 
and user interface element formatting

207
00:12:26,955 --> 00:12:30,237
and markup, integration of 
text with graphical elements

208
00:12:30,457 --> 00:12:32,824
and overall page or window layout.”

209
00:12:34,447 --> 00:12:38,455
Okay, let’s take a closer look 
at a few of the specific parameters

210
00:12:38,480 --> 00:12:43,143
collected within the parameter groups 
starting with the product line parameters.

211
00:12:43,786 --> 00:12:48,239
 Under product line parameters, 
the verticals for the work are defined.

212
00:12:48,898 --> 00:12:52,328
Vertical is a synonym for subject field

213
00:12:52,478 --> 00:12:55,251
subject matter, domain, or discipline

214
00:12:55,276 --> 00:12:59,551
and refers to the specialized subjects 
encompassed by the content.

215
00:13:00,301 --> 00:13:03,824
Defining the verticals of the work 
is an important precursor

216
00:13:03,849 --> 00:13:07,410
for determining the terminology 
and linguistic conventions

217
00:13:07,435 --> 00:13:09,457
that should be followed within the content.

218
00:13:11,302 --> 00:13:14,193
Under legal and confidentiality concerns

219
00:13:14,605 --> 00:13:16,659
important parameters are defined like

220
00:13:17,095 --> 00:13:22,165
whether or not moral rights will 
be granted to LSPs like translators

221
00:13:22,549 --> 00:13:24,479
and translation agencies.

222
00:13:25,220 --> 00:13:27,446
According to the U.S. Copyright Office

223
00:13:27,471 --> 00:13:30,570
within copyright law, 
the term moral rights

224
00:13:30,850 --> 00:13:35,046
“refers to certain noneconomic rights 
that are considered personal to an author”

225
00:13:35,447 --> 00:13:38,618
including one
“the right of attribution” or

226
00:13:38,745 --> 00:13:42,144
“the right of an author to be credited 
as the author of their work,”

227
00:13:42,169 --> 00:13:44,339
and two “the right of integrity”

228
00:13:44,652 --> 00:13:48,292
or “the right to prevent prejudicial 
distortions to the[ir] work”.

229
00:13:49,148 --> 00:13:53,687
In the U.S., translators typically don’t 
receive moral rights over their work

230
00:13:54,125 --> 00:13:56,164
but this can vary in other countries.

231
00:13:56,682 --> 00:14:00,783
For instance, federal law in Mexico 
grants these rights to translators.

232
00:14:01,271 --> 00:14:03,935
 Navigating differences in 
international federal law

233
00:14:03,960 --> 00:14:07,227
is an important aspect of 
translation and localization work.

234
00:14:09,221 --> 00:14:14,260
Data security and protection form another 
vital component of our specifications.

235
00:14:14,970 --> 00:14:18,963
Given that about 75% of 
translation work is outsourced

236
00:14:19,304 --> 00:14:23,234
it’s crucial to define how data 
will be accessed and protected.

237
00:14:24,026 --> 00:14:27,683
This is especially important 
when dealing with confidential content.

238
00:14:29,607 --> 00:14:31,552
When it comes to language parameters

239
00:14:31,797 --> 00:14:35,688
we go beyond simply specifying 
the language and variant.

240
00:14:36,310 --> 00:14:39,057
We go deeply into the demographics and

241
00:14:39,082 --> 00:14:42,104
experiential background 
of the target audience.

242
00:14:42,818 --> 00:14:44,607
This detailed understanding

243
00:14:44,632 --> 00:14:50,123
allows us to make appropriate terminology 
and stylistic choices in translation.

244
00:14:50,959 --> 00:14:54,592
I also want to emphasize the importance 
of establishing parameters

245
00:14:54,617 --> 00:14:57,672
around the language aspect 
of localization work.

