00:14:58,514 --> 00:15:01,537
While it may have been 
undervalued in recent history

247
00:15:02,054 --> 00:15:06,523
language is the primary way people 
communicate and engage with brands.

248
00:15:07,328 --> 00:15:10,851
Neglecting this component can 
contribute to user experience debt

249
00:15:11,216 --> 00:15:14,224
potentially leading to 
decreased user satisfaction

250
00:15:14,552 --> 00:15:17,584
higher churn rates, 
and negative brand perception.

251
00:15:19,446 --> 00:15:22,985
It’s worth noting that the process of 
establishing these specifications

252
00:15:23,010 --> 00:15:26,133
especially when onboarding 
new language service providers

253
00:15:26,158 --> 00:15:27,254
can take months.

254
00:15:28,035 --> 00:15:31,222
This is due to the complexity 
of addressing legal concerns

255
00:15:31,445 --> 00:15:33,508
setting up data security systems

256
00:15:33,533 --> 00:15:37,582
and establishing the additional necessary 
infrastructure for carrying out work.

257
00:15:38,464 --> 00:15:42,096
By carefully considering all these 
aspects in our specifications

258
00:15:42,405 --> 00:15:46,671
we ensure that our localization efforts 
truly speak to the intended audience

259
00:15:47,025 --> 00:15:51,025
maintaining brand integrity across 
different markets and cultures.

260
00:15:53,853 --> 00:15:56,900
Let’s move on now to 
thinking about the reality of

261
00:15:56,925 --> 00:15:59,576
the translation and localization 
production floor.

262
00:16:00,151 --> 00:16:04,026
If I’m working as a project manager 
for an organization with a heavy volume

263
00:16:04,376 --> 00:16:06,657
I do not have the capacity to

264
00:16:07,010 --> 00:16:11,049
fully review all of the content 
that’s being sent for localization

265
00:16:11,074 --> 00:16:14,826
in order to develop 
robust project specifications.

266
00:16:15,335 --> 00:16:20,038
So now I’ll discuss how generative AI 
can be incorporated to address this

267
00:16:20,300 --> 00:16:24,480
and other manual processes that 
we have in translation and localization.

268
00:16:26,938 --> 00:16:29,236
You’re likely familiar
with the software wizards

269
00:16:29,260 --> 00:16:32,313
that guide users through
the configuration process.

270
00:16:33,069 --> 00:16:37,756
A specifications wizard powered by 
generative AI can act similarly

271
00:16:38,342 --> 00:16:41,850
by analyzing the content 
for translation and localization

272
00:16:42,208 --> 00:16:44,098
to produce a more automated report

273
00:16:44,123 --> 00:16:47,926
of the work parameters that will define 
the scope and objectives for the work.

274
00:16:48,790 --> 00:16:51,220
A basic T&L Specifications Wizard

275
00:16:51,245 --> 00:16:54,814
can be achieved by prompting 
a generative AI assistant.

276
00:16:55,432 --> 00:16:57,268
For example, in this image

277
00:16:57,293 --> 00:17:01,575
a generative AI assistant has been prompted
to produce a specifications report

278
00:17:01,969 --> 00:17:05,750
that defines parameters like the 
language variant of the source text

279
00:17:06,230 --> 00:17:07,449
the primary vertical

280
00:17:07,963 --> 00:17:10,245
the author type, the content type

281
00:17:10,573 --> 00:17:13,713
and the readability level 
when a user uploads a text.

282
00:17:16,102 --> 00:17:20,602
Challenges in system prompt for producing 
this type of an automated report

283
00:17:20,627 --> 00:17:25,318
including defining a standardized ontology 
of the all of the types of content

284
00:17:25,734 --> 00:17:28,047
that humans and machines produce

285
00:17:28,072 --> 00:17:30,390
and that are translated and localized.

286
00:17:31,146 --> 00:17:33,810
Content spans many text types

287
00:17:33,835 --> 00:17:37,643
from blog posts, 
to user generated content, to reports

288
00:17:37,668 --> 00:17:39,823
statements, speeches, and articles

289
00:17:40,084 --> 00:17:41,193
and much, much more

290
00:17:41,698 --> 00:17:44,851
each text type having
its own distinct conventions

291
00:17:44,875 --> 00:17:46,745
that make the text that type.

292
00:17:47,664 --> 00:17:48,664
To illustrate

293
00:17:48,689 --> 00:17:51,489
patents use a particular language 
to describe inventions

294
00:17:51,514 --> 00:17:53,723
that is neither too broad or too narrow.

295
00:17:54,206 --> 00:17:55,698
If the language is too broad

296
00:17:55,917 --> 00:17:58,159
no new invention is actually described.

297
00:17:58,531 --> 00:18:02,289
If the language is too narrow, 
the invention is not fully protected.

298
00:18:03,175 --> 00:18:07,096
Another example of a text type is 
a fortune from a fortune cookie

299
00:18:07,121 --> 00:18:10,097
where philosophical quotes 
and encouraging predictions

300
00:18:10,122 --> 00:18:13,321
that meet strict 
character limitations are expected.

301
00:18:14,216 --> 00:18:16,692
Any ontology of
human communication and knowledge

302
00:18:16,717 --> 00:18:20,010
needs to be modeled using 
controlled language in a standardized way

303
00:18:20,035 --> 00:18:22,488
to make the information easily retrievable

304
00:18:22,730 --> 00:18:25,425
and more importantly 
actionable later downstream.

305
00:18:26,289 --> 00:18:30,446
Any system prompt therefore needs 
to strategically model complex systems

306
00:18:30,471 --> 00:18:32,929
within the limitations of 
the context window

307
00:18:32,954 --> 00:18:37,425
of information that generative AI systems 
can hold in their working memory

308
00:18:37,824 --> 00:18:42,605
when analyzing the prompt and the input 
content to produce an automated report.

309
00:18:45,814 --> 00:18:48,376
Now it’s one thing to produce 
an automated report.

310
00:18:48,856 --> 00:18:53,575
It’s another thing to make the information 
collected in the specifications actionable.

311
00:18:54,455 --> 00:18:57,533
Ideally, the automations 
we’d want to put in place

312
00:18:57,558 --> 00:19:00,542
include routing the information 
collected through the wizard

313
00:19:00,899 --> 00:19:03,492
to downstream processes in the workflow.

314
00:19:05,449 --> 00:19:08,988
We’d want the information collected 
to be used to automatically carry out

315
00:19:09,013 --> 00:19:11,716
and resolve typical 
translation readiness check issues

316
00:19:11,741 --> 00:19:13,685
associated with the content.

317
00:19:14,526 --> 00:19:18,580
We’d want the information to be 
automatically routed to expertise matching

318
00:19:18,997 --> 00:19:23,552
in selecting the best available 
translators and MT engines for the work.

319
00:19:24,565 --> 00:19:27,775
We’d want the information collected 
to be used to make recommendations

320
00:19:27,800 --> 00:19:29,893
to clients about 
the service level for their work…

321
00:19:30,766 --> 00:19:33,531
and tie the parameters 
to costs and timelines

322
00:19:33,556 --> 00:19:36,531
in order to produce 
nearly instantaneous quotes.

323
00:19:37,845 --> 00:19:42,180
We’d want the information collected to be 
used to automatically configure workflows…

324
00:19:42,925 --> 00:19:47,894
and to automatically create projects with 
the desired configuration in the TEnT.

325
00:19:49,361 --> 00:19:53,447
We’d want the information to be 
automatically routed into the style guides

326
00:19:53,472 --> 00:19:56,470
used to guide machine and human translation

327
00:19:56,895 --> 00:20:00,715
and into the final sanity checklists 
that are carried out to confirm that

328
00:20:01,035 --> 00:20:05,231
deliverables meet the requirements 
set out in the specifications.

329
00:20:06,065 --> 00:20:08,869
We’d want to do all this so that 
we’re helping our clients

330
00:20:08,966 --> 00:20:11,653
whether internal or external 
to our organization

331
00:20:11,678 --> 00:20:13,036
to meet their KPIs

332
00:20:13,420 --> 00:20:15,889
whether those KPIs are increased engagement

333
00:20:16,272 --> 00:20:18,952
a reduced number of 
customer support requests

334
00:20:19,265 --> 00:20:22,874
increased sales in the 
target market or something else.

335
00:20:24,710 --> 00:20:28,655
Being able to execute on automations 
in translation and localization

336
00:20:28,680 --> 00:20:30,204
through a system of this kind

337
00:20:30,590 --> 00:20:34,247
in a way that adds value 
to globalization strategy is doable

338
00:20:34,632 --> 00:20:38,983
and it requires a global network of 
skilled talent performing in roles like

339
00:20:39,370 --> 00:20:41,791
machine learning, software development

340
00:20:42,065 --> 00:20:44,557
product management, project management

341
00:20:44,887 --> 00:20:48,582
terminology management, 
copy editing, translation

342
00:20:48,845 --> 00:20:52,415
transcreation, subtitling, graphic design

343
00:20:52,828 --> 00:20:56,719
programming, engineering, 
localization quality assurance

344
00:20:56,934 --> 00:21:01,793
and as subject matter experts, 
in-culture experts, legal experts

345
00:21:02,109 --> 00:21:06,375
user experience designers,
in voiceover and audio engineering

346
00:21:06,837 --> 00:21:09,735
and many more roles and ways 
that have yet to be imagined.

347
00:21:11,615 --> 00:21:15,326
As we embrace the challenges and 
opportunities of global markets

348
00:21:15,738 --> 00:21:19,121
let us remember that effective 
translation and localization

349
00:21:19,467 --> 00:21:23,639
are not just about going through 
the motions to render and redesign content.

350
00:21:24,154 --> 00:21:29,021
They’re about fostering understanding 
and creating truly global experiences.

351
00:21:29,707 --> 00:21:33,191
By leveraging the power of 
technology and human expertise

352
00:21:33,599 --> 00:21:37,013
we can break down language barriers, 
connect with diverse audiences

353
00:21:37,038 --> 00:21:39,834
and drive meaningful 
growth on a global scale.

354
00:21:40,582 --> 00:21:44,254
The future of localization is 
not just about adapting content.

355
00:21:44,608 --> 00:21:49,054
It’s about crafting local experiences 
that resonate across borders and cultures

356
00:21:49,422 --> 00:21:51,844
ultimately bringing 
our world closer together.

357
00:21:53,773 --> 00:21:54,813
Thank you for your time.

